title: For Sale:  FÉG PA-63 chambered in 9X18 Makarov
postcontent:
This is a really nice little FÉG pistol that I picked up recently.  

I've always been fond of these Eastern Bloc PP/PPK style pistols.  The rock-solid dependability of Soviet regime weaponry, combined with the style and SA/DA function of the ubiquitous James Bond Walther pistol.  Reliable and compact enough to be sensible for carry, and really accurate.  What's not to like, right?

Now, some will tell you that the recoil is a little snappy (it IS a really lightweight gun after all), and the double-action trigger pull is heavy.  And it can be.  But, this particular pistol has had the sear and hammer surfaces polished, and a slightly softer hammer spring, and slightly heavier Wolff recoil spring installed.  Wolff makes several different weights of springs for both the hammer and the slide; you can dial the gun in to suit your preferences.

The original parts also come with the gun.

I bought this because it was just like the first pistol I ever bought, and I had a lot of fun with that gun.  And this one looks nicer.  But, as soon as I got this and put some work into it,  I ran across a Tokarev... the only way I can justify purchasing the new gun is to get rid of something.  

So, this is up for sale.  Check out the pictures; they tell the story pretty well.  I tried to get a good picture of the bore and chamber, but just couldn't get anything to turn out well.  Rest assured, the barrel looks as good as everything else.

Any other questions, just ask.  I am pretty busy with work this time of year, but will get back to you as quickly as possible.

Thanks for looking, and have a great day!

title: For Sale/Trade:  EDMF Trench knife
postcontent:
If you are not familiar with EDMF Google
"Eight Dollar Mountain Foundry"

Due to age and health Dale has officially retired and no more of these will ever be made. Dale built a great reputation over the years for military knives and more than a few found their way overseas on deployment.They are becoming quite collectable.

This particular model is actually a WW1 bayonet that he mated to one of his numbered, hand cast aluminium, full guard skull crusher handles and matching numbered, hand made leather sheath that the original metal scabbard locks into.

This knife has never been used or sharpened. There are some minor markings on handle and sheath just from being in a drawer for years and on the blade from being drawn from the metal scabbard.

This is a one of a kind, custom made knife from a well reputed Smith that will never make any more. He was featured in knife world magazine in 2000. I am asking $200, possibly may trade for an OTF knife.

N350 is my go to powder for 9mm. I have used it for years in this caliber, and have found none to be it's equal. I have experimented with many powders. This one has the whole package. It produces accurate, consistent, high velocity rounds without undue pressure. It meters well and is clean burning. Muzzle flash is not objectionable like other powders I have tried. It is great for both target and defensive rounds. For me, it actually produces better than advertised velocities especially near starting loads. The only drawback, as another pointed out, is that it is more expensive than other powder options. To me it is worth every penny.

This is the first powder I used when I began reloading. Since then, I have tried many different powders, but Vihtavuori N350 is the best of all by far. It is a small stick powder that meters very well(better than any other powder)in my Dillon press. I load 38 special, 357 magnum, and 45 ACP. The powder performs excellently in all of these calibers. title: For Sale:  WW2 German Submarine Badge
postcontent:
German WW2 Kriegsmarine Submarine (U-Boat) War Badge of the 3rd Reich. 

Good looking Kriegsmarine U-Boat Badge which was given usually after two war patrols. Some of the very successful commanders were awarded the badge after only one patrol.  

The U-boat War Badge was originally instituted during the First World War and awarded to recognize U-boat crews who had completed three war patrols. The badge was worn on the lower left side of the uniform and was oval shaped resembling a wreath of laurel leaves. A submarine lay across the center and the German State Crown (Reichskrone) was inlaid at the top center of the wreath.

On October 13, 1939, the U-boat War Badge was reinstituted again. It was very similar to the original badge with the exception of the Prussian crown which was replaced with a German Eagle. A swastika was added and a more modern submarine now facing towards the left was used.

There were several ways to be awarded this medal. The most common would be the completion of two war patrols because it was extremely dangerous as the U-boat has to endure constant attacks by Allied aircraft and warships.

During the later part of the war, U-boat losses were so great that many crewmen never made it past the second war patrol. Therefore, the other occasion when this badge was awarded was on completion of an especially successful first patrol or having been wounded or killed in action.
